# 

Class can be thought of as having both an objective and subjective side. On the objective side, class is a material position in society that reflects one’s relationship to the means of production, a class-in-itself, as it exists in society. On the subjective side is the realm of class consciousness, which can refer to the ideological dimensions of class and how individuals can become aware of their class position in society and act together in shared class interests.

We should resist one-sided and mechanical explanations in general, but especially regarding social class. Even in objective terms, it’s probably not possible to adequately explain it through just one or even a few lenses. We’ll start with how class under capitalism relates to who owns what and how people earn a living, probably the two best starting points for understanding class in a material sense. From there, we’ll assess each of the main social classes in more detail and explore how they relate to each other and the wider economic system.

Finally, there are some areas for more advanced analysis I’m currently considering for the future. Certainly, class is also closely interrelated with identity-based oppression under capitalism. I have written about this in the past, but it’s always worth revisiting. In Canada and countries like it, class has a deep connection to settler-colonialism, especially regarding the construction of whiteness, which has been anathema to the development of working-class consciousness. Last but not least, class under capitalism inherently has international dimensions, to the international nature of both capitalist exploitations, not just of workers, but of the entire world periphery by core nations, and also the ultimate aims of working-class struggle, in the global defeat of capitalism.

The odds are very high that if we ever encounter a mention of class in mainstream Canadian society,  it will likely be in the context of discussions around the "middle class". To a large extent, in the dominant capitalist ideology of class thinking, the middle class is the only class that exists. 

For a long time, the vast majority of people have been ideologically inoculated with the myth of the middle class-- that just about everyone in society is either a member of or should be aspiring to be in the middle class. That something called "middle class values" do or ought to be the prevalent form. As we shall see, this middle-class-centric mode of class thinking is a textbook example of false consciousness, one that obscures the reality of class divisions, by design of course.  

- Canada is probably one of the least class conscious societies in the world.

# The middle class and false consciousness

- Three-Four class model, has a powerful ideological function
- Middle class is key to that functioning
- In popular consciousness: Vaguely economic concept, but also largely vibes based
- Gut level understanding
- Few markers of important factors.

- The conceptual vagueness of middle class is by design per ideology.
- It allows just about anyone to imagine themselves as in the "middle" as a relative position.
- Only a few people are obviously excluded, the very poor and the very rich. Though the latter ought to aspire to be middle class.
- Can show the function with survey data


Across the political spectrum in Canada, which runs from barely centre-left to far-right, empty appeals to the middle class are fodder for all of the major parties and pundits. Canada's nominally social democratic party of labour, the NDP, has all but abandoned working-class politics in favour of hollow pandering to the middle class, which in their view includes some of the top income earners in the country. 

# Historical and current meanings of middle class

- The middle class is a real thing that can be defined and examined.
- Those that live on both labour and capital.
- The reality of it though, is far from it's ideological function.
- Historical: the ruling class of today was once the "middle class" of a prior age.
- Their class perspective is the dominant perspective now, just about everywhere.
- In countries like Canada, middle class consciousness prevails among most.

# The function of middle class in ideology

- Most Canadians understand themselves as middle class people, living in a middle class society, dominated by middle class values.
- This is greatly out of accord with the objective facts of class division in society.
- Engels quote on false consciousness
- https://www.marxists.org/archive/marx/works/1893/letters/93_07_14.htm
- So it is literally a form of false consciousness, that leads people to incorrect conclusions about the class structure of society and their place within it.

# Class in action

- Some define class largely or solely around income.
- OECD definition of class, middle class.
- Already we can see an important role for this class model, to blot out real class divisions.

