## Header

- How the question is asked matters, framing.
- Often, people are not given an option to identify as working class.
- The WVS is the most reliable source of survey data, using a 4 class hierarchy that includes the "working" and "lower" classes. 
- They leave it up to respondents to decide what these terms mean to them.
- So the distinctions are not precisely defined, but still, we can learn how many people have at least enough class consciousness to actually see themselves as working class, whatever that means to them.

<div style="min-height:403px"><script type="text/javascript" defer src="https://datawrapper.dwcdn.net/k1pqq/embed.js?v=1" charset="utf-8"></script><noscript><img src="https://datawrapper.dwcdn.net/k1pqq/full.png" alt="" /></noscript></div><br><br>

- When given the option, most people still don't see themselves as working class.
- Most people see themselves as middle class, mostly "lower-middle", and it is getting worse over time.
- Over the 2000s, the share of people identifying as working class took a steep dive to an all time low.
- Neoliberal ideology, but also the housing bubble probably has a lot to do with it.
- Almost nobody sees themselves as upper class, so few it's like they don't even exist. 
- Accurate at least in that the vast majority of people are not in the ruling class.
- Distinction between the "lower" and working class is also interesting.

- Certainly, those in the lower class are working class people -- proletarians -- that do not see themselves as such. It is again a case of people under-estimating their class position, but to a "lower" class that doesn't quite exist.
- Many of these people may not be working and so not see themselves as working class, but that is not quite a requirement, probably most people that do not work are still working class. Examples: retired workers, unpaid caregivers, many people with disabilities.

## Header - international comparison

- Will show in more detail later, but the objective reality is that the vast majority of people in the world -- even in core countries like Canada -- are working class.
- More than most other countries in the world, Canadian workers have been led to believe that they are "middle class".
- Canada is one of the least class conscious societies on the planet, where almost everyone thinks they are middle class, to the extent that they ever think about class at all, which is rare.
- But the version of the "middle class" -- based to a large degree on gut feeling and vibes -- they think they belong to, does not exist in reality.<br><br>

