## Header work and class thinking

- So the link between income, often the only indicator of a household's economic situation in these data sets, and self-rated class identity is all over the place. 
- WVS contains a large number of interesting variables to cross with self-rated class identity.
- The links between work and occupation and SRCP are also interesting.

- The relationship between employment status and SRCP: the closer one seems to get to being a full-time employee or having been one, the more likely one is to self-rate as middle class.
- Yet in this case, there was not a middle class consensus across all groups, re: relationship to employment.
- A majority still did identity as middle class, employed workers overwhelmingly so.
- Pausing to note the problematic nature of the category, 'housewife', the groups with the highest levels of working class consciousness were women caregivers, the unemployed, and those in "other" employment situations.<br><br>

