## Self rated class and class consciousness

- WVS has some interesting data that provide some subjective indicators of class consciousness.
- First, they had survey respondents rate their political views on a left to right scale.
- Generally, most people are centre-left, with everyone getting a bit more left as self-rated class declines.
- Most people have been shifting a bit to the left over time as well.
- The "lower" class had the most far left people, whatever that means to them. 
- The middle class actually had more people on the left (4 and under) than the working class, 30% to 25%. Though the working class's centre-left share was much bigger.
- The upper class is all over the place, probably because very few people ever identify as upper class, so small changes in response patterns can produce big relative differnces. That said, rich people were very right ring in 2020. Sounds about right.<br><br>

<div style="min-height:635px"><script type="text/javascript" defer src="https://datawrapper.dwcdn.net/rMgY5/embed.js?v=1" charset="utf-8"></script><noscript><img src="https://datawrapper.dwcdn.net/rMgY5/full.png" alt="" /></noscript></div><br><br>

- This one is interesting. One of the strongest subjective factors in middle class ideology is the belief in a meritocratic society, that the affluent are those that have worked hard for their success. It follows then, that one could move up even higher on the ideological class ladder, if one just puts in a bit more elbow grease. 
- Both middle and working class people were the most likely to believe that hard work is the key to success.
- The least likely to believe so? The self-identified upper class, a plurality of whom said that their success was mostly a matter of being connected and lucky (ie, being born into wealth).<br><br>

